The Economics of Violence
COPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, Ukraine, and elsewhere are constantly in the news, and therefore many would probably say war.
Yet this turns out to be a great mistake.
The correct answer is important when we want to find cost-effective solutions to this and other global problems.
It goes without saying that everyone would like to end war and violence, just as we would like to end poverty, hunger, and global warming and provide all people with access to education.
Yet, given limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We need to set priorities, and for this, one can use an economic cost-benefit analysis.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years, and the Copenhagen Consensus has asked some of the world's leading economists to assess which goals, in their view, would be most effective.
Is the goal of reducing violence worth the use of resources that would otherwise, for example, go into the fight against hunger?
And, if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon from Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies at the University of Oxford, violence in society – murders and especially violence against women and children – presents a far greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die from interpersonal violence, and for every two fighters who die, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and far too many countries record murder rates of over 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization describes as an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs a person their life and society $9.1 million.
Measured by national income worldwide, this form of violent crime alone costs 1.7% of the global gross social product (GDP).
Naturally, this is not a direct financial loss for the world economy, but rather a way of expressing the consequences.
If murders could be abolished, societies around the world would be better off in a way that can be quantified as 1.7% of GDP.
Compare this with the significantly lower costs of civil wars, which correspond to about 0.2% of global GDP.
This is still much less than the greatest source of violence altogether: domestic violence against women.
Based on studies published in the journal Science, 28% of all women in sub-Saharan Africa experienced violence from their partners or family members last year.
This includes women who were beaten, forced into early marriage, subjected to sexual violence, victims of crimes in the name of "honor," and subjected to female genital mutilation.
According to a cautious estimate, the societal costs of violence by partners alone amount to $440 billion or 5.2% of the global GDP.
The second largest source of violence is child abuse, which is committed in 80% of cases by parents.
The definition of child abuse varies across cultures, but roughly 15% of children experience what the UN defines as severe physical punishment each month.
These include slaps in the face, to the head or on the ears, and a quarter of these children are hit repeatedly and as violently as possible with an object.
This suffering affects about 290 million children every month.
The social costs amount to 3.6 trillion US dollars or 4.2% of the global GDP.
A tiny fraction of international aid funds is currently directed toward reducing violence in society and improving criminal justice systems.
The enormous costs borne by society and by individuals scream out for action to be taken.
Unfortunately, there are still few secure insights into where the limited resources should best be allocated.
All that can be said is that the money spent on reducing violence could be used more targetedly.
Large sums of aid are earmarked for "fragile states" to help end or prevent civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the "crime prevention" component.
Other programs may contribute indirectly, but obviously much could be improved.
Some solutions, as is clear, work very well.
More capable social institutions can reduce child abuse.
Studies in the U.S. state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained staff can reduce child abuse, improve children's quality of life and their physical and mental health, and reduce the costs of child care and legal proceedings.
A dollar spent on this program produces a benefit worth $14: it is therefore an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes must change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program in Uganda called SASA! is working.
(Kisuaheli for "Now!") has helped spread the view that violence in partnerships is unacceptable and has contributed to halving the number of cases.
This is a fantastic result, even though there is no analysis of cost efficiency available.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures have been taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach – a time limit on alcohol sales, the recovery of public spaces, and improvements in the police and justice system – the murder rate was reduced to 21 victims per 100,000 inhabitants by 2004.
That is still a high number, but much lower than the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 residents in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many violent attacks, and the findings from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be significant.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on better enforcement of existing regulations showed that violent attacks can be reduced in a very cost-effective manner, with the benefits outweighing the costs by a ratio of 17 to 1.
We still do not know enough, but two points are clear: First, domestic violence against women and children brings $8 billion in costs to society each year and thus represents a huge – and far too little addressed – global problem.
Second, there are solutions that can help address some of these problems in a very cost-effective way.
For this reason, the reduction of domestic violence should be included in the shortlist for the next development goals of the world.
